Copyright- Copyright is the legal right given to a creator to be able to do what they want with what they created and allow others to do what they want.

Copyleft-An agreement where programs or artistic work can be used and given out freely with the exception that anything made from it is under the same conditions.

Fair Use- The princible that excerpts of copyrighted material under certain circumstances can be quoted and used without permission of the copyright holder.

Free Speech- The right to express thoughts freely.

Free Software- Programes that can be edited, modified, and shared freely.

Freeware- Programs that can be used for free.

Public Domain- When something is in the state of being owned or being available to the public.

File-sharing- The ability to transfer files from one computer to another using a network on the internet.

Piracy- Hijacking of someones elses creation without their consent.

Plagiarism- Taking credit for someone elses creation or idea.

Infringement-The action of breaking the terms of a law, agreement, etc.

Proprietary-Software that is owned by an individual or a company which have major restrictions on use and the source code is kept a secret

Open Source-Original source code that is freely available and can be modified then redistributed

GNU GPL License-Gurantees end users the freedom to modify, study, and share the software

MIT License-Permits reuse of proprietary software but all copies of the software should include a copy of the MIT License terms and the copyright notice.

Apache License- Free software license written by the ASF (Apache Software Foundation) and it requires preservation of the copyright notice and disclaimer.

EULA-The End User License Agreement is a legal contract between a software application author or publisher and the use of that application

Creative Commons-A non profit organization devoted to expanding the range of creative works available for others to build upon legally and to share

